 no scholar can understand the history of Mexican communities without taking gender seriously. In legal interactions native plaintiffs and Spanish jurists confronted essential questions of identity and hegemony. At once an insightful consideration of individual experiences and sweeping paternalistic power constructs, Hijos del Pueblo contributes important new findings to the realm of gender studies and the evolution of Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFamilieszMexicozToluca de Lerdo Region. 0aFamilieszMexicozToluca de Lerdo. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozToluca de Lerdo RegionxSocial conditions. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozToluca de LerdoxSocial conditions. 0aKinshipzMexicozToluca de Lerdo Region. 0aKinshipzMexicozToluca de Lerdo. 0aSex rolezMexicozToluca de Lerdo Region. 0aSex rolezMexicozToluca de Lerdo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793880/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK